<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1278,1663]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
The specimens are normally spherical. When fixed the tunic has numerous parallel furrows due to the contraction of the body wall which closely adheres to the tunic (
<figureCitation box="[731,814,1314,1338]" captionStart="FIGURE 22. A, B" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1913,1936]" captionTargetBox="[194,1362,181,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[194,1363,181,1887]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. A, B, spicules: A, Bathypera splendens; B, Bathypera hastaefera. C, Bathypera splendens; D, Bathypera hastaefera. Scale bars: A, B = 100 µm; C, D = 3 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277191/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[783,814,1314,1338]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
D). The spicules are uniformly distributed at the colony surface, implanted on a round base and protruding in an asymmetric group of few spines of inequal length (
<figureCitation box="[159,255,1386,1410]" captionStart="FIGURE 22. A, B" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1913,1936]" captionTargetBox="[194,1362,181,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[194,1363,181,1887]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. A, B, spicules: A, Bathypera splendens; B, Bathypera hastaefera. C, Bathypera splendens; D, Bathypera hastaefera. Scale bars: A, B = 100 µm; C, D = 3 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277191/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[205,236,1386,1410]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="22.0">22</number>
B
</figureCitation>
). The spicules reach 
<number box="[487,530,1386,1410]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="600.0">600</number>
µm in length. The musculature has the same disposition as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1212,1354,1387,1411]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathyfera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[1212,1354,1387,1411]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">B. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the crossed longitudinal and transverse fibres are stronger and more extended on the body wall (
<figureCitation box="[1208,1313,1422,1446]" captionStart="FIGURE 24. A, B" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1743]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[151,1436,193,1768]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 24. A, B, musculature of the left body side: A, Bathypera splendens; B, Bathypera hastaefera. C, Bathypera splendens, specimen ventrally opened, scale bar C = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277193/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[1262,1294,1422,1446]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="24.0">24</number>
B
</figureCitation>
). All other characters are the same in both species taking in consideration the individual variations: branchial sac (
<figureCitation box="[1320,1403,1458,1482]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="35.[151,250,2004,2027]" captionTargetBox="[194,1398,183,1987]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[194,1399,183,1989]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 23. Branchial tissues: A, Bathypera splendens. B, Bathypera hastaefera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277192/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[1373,1403,1458,1482]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="23.0">23</number>
</figureCitation>
B), gut gonads and endocarps. 
<bibRefCitation author="Monniot" box="[456,784,1494,1518]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Monniot, C. &amp; Monniot, F. (1983) Ascidies antarctiques et subantarctiques: Morphologie et Biogeographie. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris, 125, 1 - 168." type="journal article" year="1983">
Monniot and Monniot (
<number box="[718,776,1494,1518]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" value="1983.0">1983</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
with few specimens estimated the differences insufficient to separate the species; the study of numerous samples collected during the CEAMARC cruise now confirms the validity of 
<taxonomicName box="[274,427,1566,1591]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hastaefera">
<emphasis box="[274,291,1568,1591]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[305,427,1566,1590]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">hastaefera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1278,1663]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<taxonomicName box="[199,348,1603,1627]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hastaefera">
<emphasis box="[199,348,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">B. hastaefera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was only recorded from the eastern part of the 
<collectingCountry box="[883,987,1602,1626]" name="Antarctica" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Antarctic</collectingCountry>
continent down to 
<quantity box="[1205,1293,1602,1626]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
. It was present in some of the CEAMARC stations in sympatry with. 
<taxonomicName box="[800,941,1638,1663]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathyfera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[800,941,1638,1663]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">B. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
